      "host": "iol.co.za",
      "text": "UCT student selected to represent SA at World Economic Forum News / 23 October 2017, 11:15pm / Staff Reporter Shamiso Kumbirai A UCT Department of Information Systems Master’s candidate has been selected to represent southern African youth at the World Economic Forum (WEF) in Davos next year. \nShamiso Kumbirai is a member of the World Economic Forum Global Shapers, a network of inspiring young people under 30 working to address local, regional and global challenges. \nThe Global Shapers Community is spread over 378 city-based hubs in 160 countries, with more than 6000 members. \nUCT said every year the WEF selects 50 Shapers from across the world to represent the voice of the youth and showcase the impactful work they are doing to change local and international communities. \nThis year, Kumbirai was selected for her work as a water engineer at global engineering and infrastructure advisory company Aurecon, and her involvement with WomEng, a multiaward- winning social enterprise working to develop the next generation of women engineering leaders in society. \n“This is a great opportunity to raise the need for infrastructure development in Africa and advocate for the advancement of African women in science, technology, engineering and maths (Stem),” Kumbirai said. \nShe is a water engineer with experience in bulk water supply and hydropower engineering across Africa. \nIn addition to her love for sustainable infrastructure development, she is passionate about advancing women in Stem. Since 2011 she has been involved with WomEng, where she served as development director in 2015. \nThrough her work in the water sector and WomEng in 2017, she was invited to host proceedings at the African Sustainability Summit and is spearheading a Sani4Schools project to improve water and sanitation facilities for a no-fee school in the Mamelodi area with over 1200 pupils. \nFor her Master’s degree, Kumbirai is focusing on participatory upgrades in large-scale water and sanitation infrastructure projects.",
