      "title": "Pulp and paper maker UPM says profit up on strong Chinese demand",
      "country": "ZA",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T08:14:40Z",
      "url": "http://www.sharenet.co.za/news/Pulp_and_paper_maker_UPM_says_profit_up_on_strong_Chinese_demand/23d255e8ca76314a82f54819e57bc0cc",
      "host": "sharenet.co.za",
      "text": "Pulp and paper maker UPM says profit up on strong Chinese demand * Q3 adjusted op profit 351 mln euros vs f'cast 321 mln * Pulp prices increase 12 percent * Shares up 1.8 percent (Adds share reaction, comment, background) HELSINKI, Oct 24 (Reuters) - Finnish pulp and paper company UPM reported quarterly profits above market expectations on the back of rising pulp prices and delivery volumes. UPM is the world's largest maker of graphic papers such as newsprint and magazine paper, where demand is falling in the West due to a shift to digital publishing. But the group has protected profitability with cost cuts and by focusing on pulp, needed not only in making paper but also in tissue products and packaging board, and which has a brighter outlook than paper. Its pulp prices increased by 12 percent in the third quarter from a year ago on the back of strong demand in China. \"The markets were favourable and we achieved good growth in delivery volumes. We also succeeded in mitigating input cost inflation with sales price increases and cost efficiency measures,\" CEO Jussi Pesonen said in a statement on Tuesday. Adjusted operating profit rose 12 percent from a year ago to 351 million euros ($413 million), compared with an average analyst expectation of 321 million. Pesonen said full-year profit would increase from last year, adding that the company would continue measures to reduce costs. Shares in the company rose 1.8 percent by 0707 GMT. \"UPM's profit machine has changed gear, (the) bottom line is clearly above forecasts ... But they weren't able to increase their core EBITDA (earnings before interests, taxes, depreciation and amortization) nor cash flow from high levels,\" analysts at Inderes Equity Research, who rate the stock \"reduce\", said. UPM also said it was considering construction of a new biorefinery in Germany costing hundreds of millions of euros, and that it plans to spend 50 million euros on expanding its plywood mill in Russia. ($1 = 0.8504 euros) (Reporting by Jussi Rosendahl and Tuomas Forsell; Editing by David Holmes) 2017-10-24 09:42:52",
