      "host": "kbc.co.ke",
      "text": "85 Kenyan financial system is likely to be thrown in serious turmoil in two months \nThe Kenyan financial system is likely to be thrown in serious turmoil in two months’ time once the new accounting system comes into force. \nThe Capital Markets Authority says most listed companies are not likely to comply with the International Financial Reporting System-IRFS9 which comes into force on the 1 st of January 2018. \nCMA Head of Market Development Justus Agoti says a taskforce that brings together all players in the financial system is compiling a report on corporate Kenya’s preparedness to migrate to the new accounting standard. \nThe clock is fast ticking towards the 1 st of January 2018. \nAnd with each passing day it is becoming clearly evident that corporate Kenya will be caught flat-footed by the new accounting regime known as the International Financial Reporting System-IFRS 9. \nPolicy makers and accountants in Kenya are not ready to implement the new standard since there are no guidelines to help in the application of IFRS-9. Also Read SMEs hard hit by political uncertainty \nThe new system was approved by global accounting bodies in 2014, allowing accounting and financial bodies to test it and generate guidelines several years in advance before the standard comes into force. \nThe CMA says the guidelines are expected to be published in December 2017, a month before the enforcement of the new standards. \nHead of Market Development Justus Agoti fears that the Kenyan capital market is likely to come under sharp pressure if listed companies fail to comply with IFRS 9. \nCompanies that fail to adapt the new accounting regime are likely to be locked out of the global financial system. \nAccording to the soundness report the Nairobi Securities Exchange, continues to weaken as political noise levels increase forcing foreign investors to dump their share for safer havens.",
